  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant penalties. The specific penalties can vary depending on the circumstances of the case, including the amount of money involved and the nature of the underlying criminal activity. Here are the general penalties for money laundering under federal law:\n\n1. **Imprisonment**:\n   - **Basic Offense**: Up to 20 years in prison.\n   - **Aggravated Offense**: If the money laundering is associated with certain other crimes (such as violations of the Bank Secrecy Act, or if it involves a financial institution), the maximum penalty can increase to 30 years in prison.\n\n2. **Fines**:\n   - **Basic Offense**: Fines can be up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n   - **Aggravated Offense**: Fines can be up to $1 million or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n\n3. **Forfeiture**:\n   - The court may order the forfeiture of any property involved in or traceable to the money laundering activity. This can include cash, bank accounts, real estate, and other assets.\n\n4. **Additional Penalties**:\n   - Individuals convicted of money laundering may also face additional penalties, including probation, supervised release, and the obligation to pay restitution to victims.\n\nThe federal statutes governing money laundering are primarily found in **18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957**. Section 1956 deals with laundering of monetary instruments, while Section 1957 deals with engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity.\n\nIt's important to note that these penalties can be enhanced if the money laundering activity is part of a larger criminal enterprise or involves significant amounts of money or international transactions. Additionally, those convicted of money laundering may also face related charges, such as conspiracy, which can carry their own separate penalties.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
